indicator.description:
1) The Kenya National Human Rights and Equality Commission prescribed in the supreme law;
2) Constitutional Commissions established from the provisions of Article 59;
2) New rules and regulation developed to operationalize KHREC Constitutional Commissions;
3) Institutional strategic plans in place and under implementation;

baseline.comment:
1) The constitution of Kenya, 2010 establishes the Kenya National Human Rights and Equality Commission (Article 59);
2) Separate Acts of parliament establish new Constitutional Commissions from the Article 59 provisions;
3) Limited institutional capacities of new Constitutional Commissions to deliver mandates;

target.comment:
1) Quasi-judicial powers of the National Gender and Equality Commission (NGEC) enhanced
2) 2,000 members of the public better understand the mandate of the Commission on Administrative Justice (CAJ)
3) 20 community elders better understand provisions of the Billl of rights and their local application;

actual.comment:
1) Quasi-judicial powers of the National Gender and Equality Commission (NGEC) enhanced through development and adoption of two sets of regulations (The Complaints handling procedure rules, and The Equality and Non-Discrimination Rules);
2) Over 3,000 persons in Embu, Kajiado, Nyeri, Tharaka Nithi and Eldoret, Migori and Vihiga Counties, increase their understanding and demand for public service from the county governments and better understand how to lodge complaints on cases of maladministration and administrative injustices
3) 25 community leaders from Mt. Elgon (18 male, 7 female) apply understanding of the Bill of Rights and Human Rights Based Approaches in local governance processes;

1)The National Gender and Equality Commission completed  audit of affirmative action application in education and employment sectors in ten counties (Muranga, Machakos, Meru, Kajiado, Trans-nzoia, Vihiga, Kirinyaga, Embu, Tharaka Nithi and Laikipia).
2) Kenya National Commission on Human Rights trained 28 staff from the Laikipia University (University Deans, Directors, HDS, Technical Team and HURI 111 teaching staff), on human rights based approach to governance and development.
3)The National Gender and Equality Commission NGEC conducted an audit of 5 county assemblies (Kilifi, Kakamega, Isiolo, Kissi, Nyandarau, Elgeyo Marakwet), on uptake of inclusion, equality and accountability principles;

indicator.description:
1) CIC engagement mechanism on constitutional implementation with MDAs developed and implemented;
2) A comprehensive CIC institutional framework that includes policies, procedures and systems, and an integrated monitoring and evaluation framework operationalized;
3) Number of sectoral, ministerial, parliamentary/senatorial and executive polices that are reviewed to ensure compliance with the letter and spirit of the Constitution of Kenya, 2010;
4) Number of legislation and administrative procedures required to implement the Constitution of Kenya, 2010 reviewed and aligned with the letter and spirit of the Constitution; 
5) Number of institutional frameworks and administrative procedures required in the implementation of the Constitution of Kenya, 2010 reviewed and or developed and adopted by various governance institutions;

baseline.comment:
1) Limited level of engagement of Ministries, Departments and Agencies (MDAs) on constitutional issues;
2) Absence of a comprehensive institutional framework to guide effective discharge of institutional mandate; 
3) Constitutional provisions including timelines for legislation to be enacted by parliament for full implementation of the constitution;
4) Limited full compliance by state organs to comply with the letter and spirit of the constitution;

target.comment:
-Forum of chair of Constitutional Commissions and Independent Offices convene and discuss working arrangements in furtherance of implementation of the Constitution;
-At least 10 Health sector policies and legislation audited to align them with the letter and spirit of the Constitution
-Progress of implementation of the Constitution for 2013/2014 presented to the Public and debates inform future actions on implementation of the Constitution

actual.comment:
-In August 2014, jointly supported by UNDP and UNWomen CIC brought together all the Constitutional Commissions and Independent Offices in a forum to assess the implementation of the Constitution from their different points of view. A set of resolutions were arrived at that would advance the common cause of these institutions over the coming year. Preceding this was a public sensitization and engagement forum on the status of implementation of the Constitution where all these institutions participated for the first time with the public in commemorating the fourth year of implementation of the Constitution and addressing local concerns in this respect;
-UNDP provided direct and indirect support to the CIC in delivering leading to it to review 15 national polices, 18 National legislations â€“ including the electoral legal framework, 7 regulations related to 7 enabling legislations, and facilitated the development of 5 sets of guidelines on administrative procedures at the National and County levels in line with the letter and spirit of the Constitution (these included an audit of 10 Health sector policies and legislation with an aim to align them with the letter and spirit of the Constitution of Kenya 2010);
-CIC assessed the status of implementation of the Constitution four years into the implementation. They used the progress report for the fiscal year 2013-2014 to assess this progress. There was an open day to share findings of the report in Muranga County where local communities were involved in examining the status and receiving the information on the status. The progress reporting was also bolstered with an examination of the status of implementation of devolved governance since the March 2013 general elections. The public in general was engaged through all forms of media to discussions on this status and therefore their awareness was further bolstered. These reports continue to be used at different levels of governance in assessing progress towards constitutionali

target.comment:
ADR research and directions for policy and legislation finalised;
2014/2015 Status of Implementation of the Constitution released;
National Academics forum aimed at embedding dialogue on Constitution implementation in the academia held and research papers developed and disseminated;

actual.comment:
-ADR policy guidance note;
-2014/2015 milestone report on implementation of the Constitution;
-Over 10 critical academic papers on embedding devolution in Kenya;

indicator.description:
1) Percentage increase in citizens use of courts and Alternative Dispute Resolution Mechanism to resolve disputes;
2) Percentage decrease in case cycle times (Disaggregated by age, gender, physical ability);
3) Number of functional and coordinated administration of justice mechanisms at the national and devolved levels;
4) Proportion of training (to Judicial staff and Judicial Officers) that translates to expeditious delivery of Justice;
4) Percentage increase in knowledge development, sharing and learning platforms;
5) Number of institutional policies that support JTF implementation;

baseline.comment:
1) Low levels of physical and functional access to courts;
2) Inequitable access to justice by Citizenâ€™s; 
3) Limited coordination of the Institutions involved in the chain of administration of Justice;
4) A Judicial culture that is retrogressive and impacts on effective, efficient and expeditious delivery of justice;
5) A Judiciary Transformation Framework (JTF) with aspirations for comprehensive reform of the institution of the Judiciary;

actual.comment:
a) A fully fledged Judiciary Media center was refurbished and equipped at the Milimani Law Courts, one of the largest courts in Kenya. The Judiciary Media Center is the first of its kind in Kenya advancing the principles of people participation in the process of delivery of justice and opening up the Judiciary to the public through different mediums. Similarly, court reports from across the Country were trained and accredited as part of this process with a view to enhancing partnership between the Judiciary and the Media and professionalizing Court reporting. This was done in Conjunction with the Media Council of Kenya;
b) A legal officer was recruited and provided to the Office of the Deputy Chief Justice to strengthen research capacity and provision of advice in line. Similarly a legal researcher and rapporteur was recruited and provided on a short term basis to the ODCJâ€™s office to enjoin with the process of development of policy guidelines on administration of Bail and Bond; 
c) UNDP supported the publication of the 2013/2014 annual State of the Judiciary and Administration of Justice;
d) UNDP provided technical support and facilitated the fact finding missions of the taskforce established in the framework of the National Council for the Administration of Justice (NCAJ) to develop Draft policy guidelines on administration of Bail and Bond. By the close of the year there was an advance draft framework awaiting validation by stakeholders. This will be instrumental in advancing access to justice issues in Kenya;

target.comment:
a) The National Policy on Bail and Bond is finalised, internally reviewed, approved, presented to the Chief Justice and Launched in a National public event;
b) Schemes of service for all Judiciary staff are generated and validated in preparation for submission to the Management Committee;
c) Draft Registry Manual for the Magistrates Court (Including Kadhis Court) developed and validated nationally;

actual.comment:
a) A National Policy on Bail and Bond Launched. The policy and guidelines will guide police and judicial officers in the application of laws that provide for bail and bond. 
b) Schemes of service for Judicial Officers completed and presented to Judiciary management;
c) A draft Magistrates court (Including Kadhis Courts) registry manual developed, subjected to stakeholder review and validated;
